b'' b'' b'yes i am aware coreldraw exports in scodal...' b'... but if you try to export in scodal with a bitmap' b'it will say something like "cannot export...' b'...if anyone out there knows a way around this' b'i am all ears.' b'' b'i think one (not ideal) solution is to use the' b"tracing utility (can't remember the name, sorry!)" b'included in the corel draw s/w pack. it can convert' b'bitmaps to corel art format. these can then be' b'imported into a drawing rather than the bitmap.' b'result the file is completely in corel format and' b"can be scodal'ed no problem!" b'' b'but the slight problem with this, which makes the' b'solution less than idea, is that the trace utility' b'spits out many more points than are necessary to' b'define the shapes being traced. straight lines and' b'curves are both traced as many short segments.' b'' b'so... the scodal taking *much* longer to' b'image.' b'' b'the obvious solution is time-consuming stripping' b'out the extra points by hand using corel.' b'' b'ouch!' b"i've done it a few times b'' b'...i was just wondering if there was anything out there' b'that just did the bitmap to scodal part a tad cheaper.' b'^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^' b'jeff lyall' b'' b"as i say, if you don't mind the problems, go via the route..." b'bitmap corel (via trace) b'hand trimming (using corel)!!! b'combine with main corel pic (via import) scodal' b'' b'cheers,' b'toby' b'____________________________________._.____._.__________._.__________._.______' b'____________________________________! b'___! b'___! toby freeman b'___! glasgow university b'___!____________________________!___! b'____________________________________!_!____!_!__\\____/__!_!_!_____/___\\___!___' b'' 